Some browsers are able to parse correctly the following:
```javascript
        [{
            trigger: "a:contains(EN)",
            content: "Change Lang to EN",   
        },
        {
            trigger: "a:contains(ES)",
            content: "Change Lang to ES",   
            extra_trigger: "a[data-lang=en_US].active",
        },]
```
but the sad thing is we have to do it for all the browsers so the correct syntax would be:
```javascript
        [{
            trigger: "a:contains(EN)",
            content: "Change Lang to EN",   
        },
        {
            trigger: "a:contains(ES)",
            content: "Change Lang to ES",   
            extra_trigger: "a[data-lang=en_US].active",
        }]
```
this is allowed from [JSON5](http://json5.org/)(specified in ES5) towards so the phantom browser does not handle it and errors can be caused on tests.

This might be a more permanent solution to the issues @stub42 is facing with the apt layer. A simplification of the issue in question:

```python
@when("config.changed.packages")
@when("apt.sources.configured")
def  install_packages():
    # ...

@when("config.changed.sources")
def configure_sources():
    # ...
```

The issue here is that `configure_sources` has to be run before `install_packages` if both `config.changed.packages` and `config.changed.sources` are set.

I'd like to find a solution that isn't tied to implementation details of the reactive framework (ie. the fact that a "run" starts as part of a hook). Nor to the technical details of this issue. An [`@preflight` decorator](https://github.com/juju-solutions/charms.reactive/pull/20) solves this issue because config cannot change during an reactive run. However, other stuff can change such as files changing or states being added and removed. We also want to cover those cases.

I don't think the reactive framework can currently solve this issue in a clean way.

A solution for this problem that fits the reactive approach better is to be able to link states together so that state changes can trigger other state changes without the need for a handler to run.

```python
# Every time `config.changed.sources` gets set, then `apt.sources.configured` gets removed
# immediately; before running the next handler.
reactive.if_this_then_remove('config.changed.sources', 'apt.sources.configured')

@when("config.changed.packages")
@when("apt.sources.configured")
def  install_packages():
    # ...

@when("config.changed.sources")
def configure_sources():
    # ...
    set_state('apt.sources.configured')
```

I think that solves @stub42's issue. Thoughts?

# Behavioral Change Between SocketsHttpHandler and WinHttpHandler with HTTP method names

A behaviour change between using `WinHttpHandler` (the 2.0 default) and `SocketsHttpHandler` (the new 2.1 default) with `HttpClient` when making HTTP requests with a user-specified HTTP method string that is lower-case that may cause HTTP requests to be rejected as invalid.

# General

I help maintain an ASP.NET Core 2.0 application which we recently upgraded to ASP.NET Core 2.1. This application is hosted on AWS EC2 instances with IIS as a reverse proxy, with client requests being routed to AWS' Application Load Balancer (ALB).

In the end-to-end tests for the application, we have some test cases that perform some validation against the application as part of the deployment into AWS, one of which, when simplified, looks like this:

```csharp
[Theory]
[InlineData("get")]
[InlineData("head")]
[InlineData("options")]
public async Task Validate_Application_Health(string httpMethod)
{
    var requestUri = new Uri("https://my-application-load-balancer");

    using (var httpClient = new HttpClient())
    {
        using (var request = new HttpRequestMessage(new HttpMethod(httpMethod), requestUri))
        {
            using (var response = await httpClient.SendAsync(message))
            {
                Assert.Equal(response.StatusCode, HttpStatusCode.OK);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Upon upgrading the application to run on ASP.NET Core 2.1, when the application was first deployed into AWS and the tests run, they failed with HTTP 400 responses instead of the expected HTTP 200. The same test pointed at the deployed 2.1 application targeting 2.0 locally passed as expected, indicating the difference was somewhere in the tests client-side.

After various bits of trial and error, I eventually narrowed the issue down to the use of _lower case_ HTTP methods being passed as argument to the `HttpMethod` constructor. It appears that ALB rejects HTTP requests that are using lowercase HTTP methods, as changing the test case to send through _upper case_ strings when using 2.1 made them pass again ([StackOverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/a/50685566/1064169)).

I guess something in the previous stack normalised the HTTP methods to upper case before sending them over the wire, but from [looking at the code](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/eaba0885c15404b41aa9a5113cf7cc8e7252053c/src/System.Net.Http/src/System/Net/Http/SocketsHttpHandler/HttpConnection.cs#L377) this appears to not be the case in the new 2.1 networking stack for `HttpClient`.

While this was easy to workaround and fix, it is a change in behaviour between 2.0 and 2.1 (at least on Windows) that as far as I'm aware isn't documented and is sort-of a breaking change, so I thought it best to report this as an issue, even if it does end up being closed as _By Design_ or _Won't Fix_.

Below is a repro console application the exhibits the difference in behaviour. On my machine, it outputs the following when the request URI is a valid AWS ALB:

```console
WinHttpHandler GET -> OK
WinHttpHandler get -> OK
SocketsHttpHandler GET -> OK
SocketsHttpHandler get -> BadRequest
HttpClient GET -> OK
HttpClient get -> BadRequest
```

<details>

`HttpMethodCase.csproj`
```xml
<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
  <PropertyGroup>
    <LangVersion>latest</LangVersion>
    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>
    <TargetFramework>netcoreapp2.1</TargetFramework>
  </PropertyGroup>
  <ItemGroup>
    <PackageReference Include="System.Net.Http.WinHttpHandler" Version="4.0.0" />
  </ItemGroup>
</Project>
```

`Program.cs`
```csharp
using System;
using System.Net.Http;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

namespace HttpMethodCase
{
    internal static class Program
    {
        internal static async Task Main(string[] args)
        {
            var requestUri = new Uri("http://url-for-a-valid-aws-application-load-balancer/");

            using (var handler = new WinHttpHandler())
            {
                await SendAsync("GET", requestUri, handler);
                await SendAsync("get", requestUri, handler);
            }

            using (var handler = new SocketsHttpHandler())
            {
                await SendAsync("GET", requestUri, handler);
                await SendAsync("get", requestUri, handler);
            }

            await SendAsync("GET", requestUri);
            await SendAsync("get", requestUri);
        }

        private static async Task SendAsync(
            string httpMethod,
            Uri requestUri,
            HttpMessageHandler handler = null)
        {
            using (var httpClient = handler == null ? new HttpClient() : new HttpClient(handler, disposeHandler: false))
            {
                using (var request = new HttpRequestMessage(new HttpMethod(httpMethod), requestUri))
                {
                    using (var response = await httpClient.SendAsync(request))
                    {
                        await Console.Out.WriteLineAsync($"{handler?.GetType().Name ?? "HttpClient"} {httpMethod} -> {response.StatusCode}");
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

</details>

